WEBVTT

00:01.102 --> 00:01.234
.

00:01.734 --> 00:03.104
- * Well

00:03.137 --> 00:04.038
* Well, my love

00:04.072 --> 00:08.209
- You think this is a good spot?
[laughter]

00:08.242 --> 00:09.377
- Ah, I'll see you inside.

00:09.410 --> 00:12.780
Remember, if you get any central
lines today, I'm your man.

00:12.813 --> 00:13.947
- And if I don't?

00:13.981 --> 00:17.618
- * Now I'm trying to wake up
from this *

00:17.651 --> 00:20.254
- Honey, you're still bleeding.

00:20.288 --> 00:24.525
Mm, yeah, I think I'll be doing
those central lines myself.

00:24.558 --> 00:26.527
- [chuckles]
Give me a break.

00:26.560 --> 00:27.595
See you.
- [laughs]

00:32.400 --> 00:33.801
- [sighs] The coast is clear.

00:33.834 --> 00:36.137
Save some lives today,
Dr. Halstead.

00:36.170 --> 00:38.239
- I'll try, Dr. Shore,
and you down in path,

00:38.272 --> 00:39.540
enjoy your day with the dead.

00:39.573 --> 00:42.210
- Always do.
[both laugh]

00:42.243 --> 00:45.513
- * We turn our backs
to the wind *

00:51.352 --> 00:53.254
- Hey, you look cheerful today.

00:53.287 --> 00:56.424
- Well, you know, I like
to see the ED as half-full.

00:58.459 --> 01:00.628
- Dr. Halstead, Dr. Manning.

01:00.661 --> 01:04.331
- Clarke.

01:04.364 --> 01:05.566
So how you two doing?

01:05.599 --> 01:07.235
- What?

01:07.268 --> 01:10.138
- You and Jeff.
- What are you talking about?

01:10.171 --> 01:13.174
- Natalie, everyone knows.

01:13.207 --> 01:15.243
It's good.
It's--you know,

01:15.276 --> 01:16.477
you seem a lot happier lately.

01:16.510 --> 01:17.345
It's nice.

01:17.378 --> 01:19.480
- Okay, but when you say
everybody, wh--

01:19.513 --> 01:23.151
- ED staff,
ambulance drivers, EMTs.

01:23.184 --> 01:24.418
- Huh.
- The crazy guy out front

01:24.452 --> 01:26.220
who thinks he's Jesus.

01:26.254 --> 01:30.458
- Okay, so about the same people
who know about you and Nina.

01:30.491 --> 01:33.427
- Wait, seriously?

01:35.196 --> 01:37.465
- Incoming.
- Dr. Choi?

01:37.498 --> 01:40.134
We're going to room two.

01:40.168 --> 01:42.336
- Edward Hall, 82,
he passed out in his apartment,

01:42.370 --> 01:44.405
was awake when we got there,
vitals stable.

01:44.438 --> 01:46.707
- Mr. Hall, how are you feeling?
- Head hurts.

01:46.740 --> 01:47.875
You got an Aspirin?

01:47.908 --> 01:49.510
- He's never done this before.

01:49.543 --> 01:51.679
He was just walking to
the bedroom, and he fell down.

01:51.712 --> 01:53.447
- We're gonna take care of you,
Mr. Hall, okay?

01:53.481 --> 01:57.485
On my count, one, two, three.

01:57.518 --> 01:58.886
Okay, let's get an H and H.

01:58.919 --> 02:00.254
[speaks indistinctly]

02:04.525 --> 02:06.294
Get Dr. Rhodes.
- Okay.

02:06.327 --> 02:09.229
Have you experienced any recent
neck pain, trouble swallowing?

02:09.263 --> 02:11.332
- Swallowing?
- Your neck is swollen.

02:11.365 --> 02:13.367
How long has it been like that?

02:13.401 --> 02:16.637
- I don't--swallowing?
- He's in and out mentally,

02:16.670 --> 02:18.639
mostly out,
but I take care of him.

02:18.672 --> 02:21.375
- Are you his daughter?
- No, I'm his girlfriend.

02:21.409 --> 02:23.377
It's okay, Eddie.
You're gonna be all right.

02:23.411 --> 02:24.945
- What do we got?
- Neck swelling

02:24.978 --> 02:25.979
with a bruit.
I'm thinking there's

02:26.013 --> 02:27.948
a compressive mass in his chest,
possibly a tumor.

02:27.981 --> 02:29.650
- Oh, my God, do you think
he has cancer?

02:29.683 --> 02:30.951
- Could be.

02:30.984 --> 02:32.320
If it's pressing on his heart
or carotids,

02:32.353 --> 02:33.587
that would explain
his passing out.

02:33.621 --> 02:34.688
- And if that's the case,
we're gonna have

02:34.722 --> 02:35.623
to operate to remove it.

02:35.656 --> 02:38.259
- Well, just do whatever
it takes, please.

02:38.292 --> 02:39.627
Just take care of him.

02:39.660 --> 02:41.262
- Tell radiology
we're on our way up

02:41.295 --> 02:43.764
for a neck and chest CT with
contrast, then up to the OR.

02:43.797 --> 02:46.534
- Whoa, whoa, whoa, please stop.
Don't take him anywhere.

02:46.567 --> 02:47.535
- Excuse me, sir,
can I help you?

02:47.568 --> 02:48.936
- This is my father.

02:48.969 --> 02:50.971
He doesn't want any of this.

02:51.004 --> 02:52.373
And that bitch has no right

02:52.406 --> 02:54.508
to make any decisions
about his health.

02:54.542 --> 02:57.511
[dramatic music]

02:57.545 --> 03:04.618
*

03:08.722 --> 03:09.990
- The fact is my father
doesn't want

03:10.023 --> 03:11.592
any extraordinary measures
taken.

03:11.625 --> 03:12.626
- He never said that.

03:12.660 --> 03:13.927
- When his mind
first started to go,

03:13.961 --> 03:15.629
he made his wishes
clear to me.

03:15.663 --> 03:17.898
- Dr. Choi, what are
Mr. Hall's options?

03:17.931 --> 03:19.900
- The scan suggests
he has a thymoma.

03:19.933 --> 03:20.768
If we treat supportively,

03:20.801 --> 03:22.803
he'll probably have four
to six months,

03:22.836 --> 03:25.573
but if we excise the tumor,
we can prolong his life

03:25.606 --> 03:28.909
significantly, as I'm sure
our surgeons can attest.

03:28.942 --> 03:31.545
- Surgery's definitely
an option.

03:34.715 --> 03:35.783
- Yes, uh,

03:35.816 --> 03:38.586
though surgery
does come with risk,

03:38.619 --> 03:41.455
a successful operation
could result in a total cure.

03:41.489 --> 03:43.524
- He's 82 and demented.

03:43.557 --> 03:45.493
You want to put him
through an operation? For what?

03:45.526 --> 03:47.461
- He just said he could live.
- Yeah, and he could be left

03:47.495 --> 03:49.029
hooked up to wires and tubes
for who knows how long?

03:49.062 --> 03:50.464
No.
- You can't do this.

03:50.498 --> 03:51.932
You can't just
let him kill Eddie.

03:51.965 --> 03:54.602
- I am trying to honor
my father's wishes.

03:54.635 --> 03:55.769
- All right, enough.

03:55.803 --> 03:59.740
Look, we all understand this
is a very sensitive issue,

03:59.773 --> 04:03.511
but what matters here is who has
the legal authority

04:03.544 --> 04:06.514
to make Mr. Hall's decisions.

04:06.547 --> 04:08.749
- Well, as far as
the hospital's concerned,

04:08.782 --> 04:10.918
with no advance directive
in place

04:10.951 --> 04:12.920
the surrogate
decision-making power

04:12.953 --> 04:14.054
goes to the next of kin,

04:14.087 --> 04:16.857
which, in this case,
is Mr. Hall's son.

04:16.890 --> 04:18.024
- No.
- Thank you.

04:18.058 --> 04:19.327
- Ms. Goodwin,
all due respect,

04:19.360 --> 04:21.862
but my job is to do whatever it
takes to keep my patients alive.

04:21.894 --> 04:23.063
- Dr. Choi, you heard him.

04:23.096 --> 04:24.765
Our hands are tied.

04:24.798 --> 04:26.567
- So that's it?

04:26.600 --> 04:27.868
You're just gonna
let Eddie die?

04:27.901 --> 04:30.671
- I'm sorry.

04:36.877 --> 04:39.647
- Hey, you got a bounce-back
in three.

04:43.617 --> 04:47.921
- Hey, Haley. Back so soon?
- I was afraid you'd miss me.

04:47.955 --> 04:51.859
- Always. You still throwing up?
- No, that's all better.

04:51.892 --> 04:53.861
- Right after we saw you,
what, three days ago?

04:53.894 --> 04:56.029
She started getting
a fever and chills.

04:56.063 --> 04:58.966
- We tried ibuprofen,
but it didn't come down.

04:58.999 --> 05:00.501
- You did the right thing.

05:00.534 --> 05:01.969
When'd you finish your last
round of chemo?

05:02.002 --> 05:03.937
- Yesterday.
- Usually the chemo fevers

05:03.971 --> 05:06.306
don't last this long.
[beeping]

05:08.542 --> 05:11.512
- Or get this high, 103.

05:11.545 --> 05:12.746
- Do you think
something's wrong?

05:12.780 --> 05:15.749
- Hard to say. The cancer meds
do knock down her immune system,

05:15.783 --> 05:18.018
so I wouldn't be surprised if
she got some sort of infection.

05:18.051 --> 05:20.020
- But probably nothing
to worry about?

05:20.053 --> 05:21.755
- Probably not,
but I would like

05:21.789 --> 05:22.956
to start her
on some antibiotics

05:22.990 --> 05:25.593
and get labs and cultures
just to be safe.

05:25.626 --> 05:27.661
Looks like we'll be spending
a little more time together.

05:29.096 --> 05:31.799
I'll be back shortly.

05:32.800 --> 05:34.502
- Ready to head to the farm?

05:34.535 --> 05:35.869
- Nurse, can you
please come here?

05:35.903 --> 05:38.906
- Sorry, I'm slammed.
- Oh.

05:38.939 --> 05:42.042
- The farm?
- Uh-huh, you want to come?

05:42.075 --> 05:43.744
- Sure. What's the farm?

05:43.777 --> 05:45.646
- You'll see.

05:47.781 --> 05:49.917
- Please, I need to leave.
- Okay.

05:49.950 --> 05:51.952
- No, I got to go. Can you just
take this tube out of my nose?

05:51.985 --> 05:53.120
- Mr. Jones--
- Everything okay?

05:53.153 --> 05:54.655
- He wants to leave.

05:54.688 --> 05:56.123
- Bowel obstructions,
even partial ones,

05:56.156 --> 05:58.058
can become life-threatening
situations.

05:58.091 --> 05:59.760
We can't discharge you
until it's cleared.

05:59.793 --> 06:01.795
- It doesn't hurt anymore.
- Look, I understand,

06:01.829 --> 06:04.565
but your output
is still too high.

06:04.598 --> 06:05.699
Let's see if I can
feel any--

06:05.733 --> 06:10.170
- No! I just--I don't like
to be touched.

06:10.203 --> 06:12.940
- How we doing in here?

06:16.910 --> 06:18.779
- Give the tube
a little more time.

06:18.812 --> 06:20.881
I promise we'll get you home
as soon as possible.

